SIMPLE: indifference
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Indifference
<hw>In*dif"fer*ence</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>indifferentia</ets> similarity, lack of difference: cf. F.
<ets>indiff⟦eacute⟧rence</ets>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>The quality or state of being indifferent, or not
making a difference; lack of sufficient importance to constitute a
difference; absence of weight; insignificance.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Passableness; mediocrity.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Impartiality; freedom from prejudice, prepossession,
or bias.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He . . . is far from such <qex>indifference</qex> and equity as
ought and must be in judges which he saith I assign.</q> <rj><qau>Sir T.
More.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Absence of anxiety or interest in respect to what is
presented to the mind; unconcernedness; <as>as, entire
<ex>indifference</ex> to all that occurs</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Indifference</qex> can not but be criminal, when it is
conversant about objects which are so far from being of an indifferent
nature, that they are highest importance.</q>
<rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Carelessness; negligence; unconcern; apathy;
insensibility; coldness; lukewarmness.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Indifferency</ent>⟦br⟧
